Surprisingly I completed this game w/o resorting to walkthroughs or buying hints. For that, I must give 5 stars, as the game is fun and has enjoyable lively chamber music and very pretty visuals of nature and castle furnishings. There are also beautiful objects to view. I play the game with Magnification gestures (Settings ¬ª Accessibility ¬ª Magnification gestures) turned on so that I can zoom in to see distant statues and such in greater detail. I solved a couple or so puzzles before finding the clues for them but they had limited variables, and I didn't find any difficult puzzles that didn't have an associated solution object to be found later in the game, sometimes much later. Examine carefully, the objects in each scene, including what might be on the floors and hidden inside other objects. Taking notes as someone mentioned is a good idea for those whose memory isn't as keen as some or for those who'd rather play the game over a few days rather than attempt to race through it within several hours. I also got the game on sale for free. That's a smart incentive to get more people to try the game, as many will be making purchases of their other titles after playing a free full game

that the game has 50+ screens, and all the puzzles involve finding a clue 
in a completely unrelated area several screens away, playing without fast 
travel was an exercise in frustration. Also got stuck a couple of times 
because I couldn't see collectable items on top of the similarly coloured 
surface they were sitting on. It's worth a punt if it's on sale, as long as 
you bear the above in mind.

replyContent: Hi Peter, Sorry you are having difficulty with the maze. The perspective is always facing north, as you turn left or right, etc. you are still facing north. You can email me at the support email address and I can send you an overview image of the maze. We will also be adding a walkthrough video to youtube in a few days. Thank you.

content: Detailed, realistic and enjoyable.  Functions well. UPDATE: I replayed the game to see what the new features looked like after the update; I didn't notice a difference except that the inventory was not fully visible.  If I'd been playing for the first time, that would have made the game quite difficult or frustrating.  I chose not to pay more for fast travel, but I'll gladly buy their new games for an up-front price.

This happens to older gamers with repetitive strain injuries and years working at computer jobs. üòä Be kind to us. After my shoulder feels better, I will definitely buy the sequel. Oh, nice background music, too! Kudos, Lone Wolf!

This game is good value for the money.  I put it on my phone as I was going to be traveling and wanted something to do on the plane and hanging around airports, etc.  I ended up getting several hours of game play.  The puzzles aren't terribly hard, my biggest problem was trying to remember where I had seen things. There is a layout available of all the locations you have been to, and a hint system that gives you just enough of a nudge in the right direction (I used it a few times!).  I really miss the old adventure style games (King's Quest, Zork, etc.) so if the folks over at Lone Wolf wanted to create something like that I will buy it :-)!  But this game is a start in that direction and I will probably buy another one in the series.

replyContent: Hi, Thank you for playing the game and sorry you had problems with that puzzle. You will need to turn all of the lights off to solve the puzzle. When you touch a dot it will toggle the surrounding dots on or off. We will be posting a walkthrough video on youtube in the next few days. Thank you.
